October 23, 2017 JD Keyboard, PC/Gaming Peripherals, Reviews

Motospeed K87S RGB Keyboard

 

Hate or love the RGB craze, this board is definitely entertainment for your eyes. This is the Motospeed K87S. Gear Best sent it over to me to review, so here it is. There’s RGB in the keycaps as well as in the base of the board. Both of which come with their own separate lighting features. I figured I’d tell you the price immediately so I’m not leaving you guessing till the end of the video.

Build quality:

  • Overall it’s pretty solid. The K87s features an aluminum base plate and thick clear plastic layer beneath for rigidity while also maintaining transparency for the LED’s in the bottom. The board does not twist or bend when I try contorting the body.
  • The keycaps are made very well with double molded caps with transparent lettering and symbols for the light to illuminate properly.
  • The board also features either a red or blue Outemu switch, personally I went with the red switch since it’s a lot quieter than blues. The Outemu switch is their own brand of switch, but it is a well-made switch nonetheless. The red switch requires a little more actuation force than Cherry Mx Reds, but they feel tactile and responsive regardless. I couldn’t find any information on the switches and their exact actuation force or travel distance.
  • These switches definitely work for gaming and typing as any other mechanical keyboard should.
  • The texture on the keycaps are a smooth well-polished plastic which is comfortable for long sessions of typing.
  • The travel distance for the actuation point is about half way down
  • There is no ghosting either, allowing for multiple key presses at once without mysterious letters showing up. So yeah, it works for gaming.

RGB’sssssssssssssssssss

  • Yeah, the focal point of this keyboard is definitely the RGB’s. They are illuminated very well in the keycaps offering a soft glow around the keycaps, which in my opinion is one of the best looks for backlighting that there can be.
  • The lighting in the base is good as well, it offers a layer of fluidity that really makes this board look amazing.
  • You change the key cap coloring options by pressing FN + INS and then based on the color mode you can change the color by pressing FN + DEL.
  • To change the base lighting, press FN + PU and to change the color press FN + PD. Last thing to note is that you can change the speed of the lighting by pressing FN + left arrow key to speed up and FN + right arrow key to slow down; and you can change the brightness level by pressing FN + up arrow key to increase brightness and FN + down arrow key for the opposite.
  • A little bonus feature for this board is there are predefined lighting options for games such as LOL and COD and what not, once again accessed by the FN key.

Basic fetures:

  • There are no drivers or software as you could probably guess.
  • The cable is rubber it is not braided
  • The USB connector is USB 2.0
  • The font style is the one of which you would find on cheaper keyboards. Again, I am not a fan of this font style, the letters and numbers look fine, but the shift, ins, del, hm, pu, and pg down keys I do not like. That’s primarily preference though.

Verdict:

I really like this keyboard. I enjoy it a lot. It’s well made, looks great, and games all at a respectable price. I believe this is a nice addition to a setup to really stand out and goes along with almost any color scheme. I love the white keycaps and the switches are quality. A little more force to push down than some other red switches, but nothing that negates from the overall experience. The only things I don’t like are cosmetic, which is the font style and the wave animation is a little choppy, even when sped up. I would’ve liked a numpad, but that’s honestly preference since a lot people don’t even use them…well I do. Now I got this board from gearbest.com and you guys can check them out in the description below to find a lot of electronics and cheaper brands with decent quality. The site is really popular with consumers all over the world. This keyboard in particular goes on sale in which you can score a good deal on, you may be able to find this board cheaper at some other retailers, but I would still recommend checking out gearbest to see their tablets, phones, and drones that are cheaper by a significant margin due to offer cheaper and off brands. So worth the check.

You can purchase adn check out the Motospeed K87S here: https://goo.gl/sziGuC

I hope you all enjoyed the review and thanks for reading!
